{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "66bcbda3ae81d148616b12e5", "type": "singleCorrect", "level": 1, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": 45, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "MOG", "classes": [], "exams": ["615d76e4c52ffa3c944600e1"], "subjects": ["615d70bd9948bc1b21da2b1f"], "chapters": ["615d6fee2b295b085ab6ebba"], "topics": [], "concepts": [], "microConcepts": [], "questionLabels": [], "previousYearPapers": [{"_id": "64b850022a7d64ecd80b00a2", "title": "NEET 2003", "isVisible": true}], "question": {"text": "Formation of a solution from two components can be considered as:\n(i) Pure solvent $\\rightarrow$ separated solvent molecules $\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_1$\n(ii) Pure solute $\\rightarrow$ separated solute molecules, $\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_2$\n(iii) Separated solvent and solute molecules $\\rightarrow$ solution, $\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_3$\nSolution so formed will be ideal of:", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "DhD1p", "text": "$\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_{\\text {soln }}=\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_1+\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_2+\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_3$", "image": null, "isCorrect": true}, {"id": "hnTFZ", "text": "$\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_{\\text {soln }}=\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_1+\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_2-\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_3$", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "Sb9FS", "text": "$\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_{\\text {soln }}=\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_1-\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_2-\\Delta \\mathrm{H}_3$", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "WkC31", "text": "$\\mathrm{AH}_{\\text {soln }}=\\mathrm{AH}_3-\\mathrm{AH}_1-\\mathrm{AH}_2$", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "So the enthalpy of solution can either be endothermic, exothermic or neither $(\\Delta$ Hsolution $=0)$, depending on how much heat is required or release in each step. If $\\Delta$ Hsolution $=$ 0 , then the solution is called an ideal solution and if\r\n$\\Delta$ Hsolution $>0$ or $\\Delta$ Hsolution $< 0$, then these solutions are called non-ideal solutions.\r\nRelated Theory\r\nThe enthalpy of solution depends on the strengths of intermolecular forces of the solute and solvent. If the solution is ideal, and $\\Delta \\mathrm{H}$ solution $=0$, then\r\n$\\begin{aligned}\r\n& \\Delta H_{\\text {solution }}=\\Delta H_1+\\Delta H_2+\\Delta H_3=0 \\\\\r\n& \\Delta H_1+\\Delta H_2=-\\Delta H_3\r\n\\end{aligned}$", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "masterId": "MOGNEPYQ64105767", "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "bucket": "", "isRemoved": false, "updatedAt": "2024-09-02T06:31:32.542Z", "updated_by": "65d0c176a8f74604505ba6f6", "cpyqbSubjects": ["615f0cf69476412f48314dac", "616057040283de43c87e3e16", "61bb58281213731910ea0b71", "6160579d0283de43c87e3e1f", "61964f94a5a526011886801e", "61c055f6e8ce0dc8a5c62d34", "61a8a2cce8ce0dc8a5c62d2e", "6160577e0283de43c87e3e1c", "616057210283de43c87e3e19", "629105adee9e3ae00d63352c", "62962075e7f8e9ac4daeafd8", "629f385f263330a77be9fa7e", "629f39e4ac11b26562e0625c", "61964ff3a5a5260118868022", "64d50c263df7f4a7f3017f70", "66b79b89d4b564dfab4f94d0", "678ea9a09cc79e5f592bdc12", "67fa602f4468eb1307ceb0ae", "6807d350647479b8e869647a"], "cpyqbChapters": ["61c089a84debc4a042f8ee21", "61964ca7ddda908e3fa7fe51", "61e7bd7b8e5525f8a94b4576", "616024c9726050da762a9cd9", "616024c970aaf69ed7837139", "616024cb524778737b091ecd", "61964ca77f311f8177e3dbda", "616024cb87f7d56df275cd4e", "616024ca2399876bbf4489a0", "61bb822386e6555c31dfb117", "629f3901a7af7bb386a6e010", "629f3a880ea25a1f67a677c8", "629109e0a17ebd5e933690a0", "6296211a8e2b9bad16620079", "64eb06cf3118f713ecfef113", "66d58542a75f05ee8564f5c1", "67921d741d5b5072da5e9b31", "67fdff41378e1624ea7b6941", "68091fe73a10446a207fdc1b"], "cpyqbExams": ["616059d70283de43c87e3e24", "616059730283de43c87e3e22"]}}